hands_on_practices.solution:
To determine the properties of the newly formed DNA junction, we must first analyze the DNA ends produced by each restriction enzyme and then determine the sequence created by their ligation.

Step 1: Analyze the cleavage by BamHI.
The BamHI recognition sequence is 5'-GGATCC-3'. Its complementary strand is 3'-CCTAGG-5'. The enzyme cleaves between the two G's on the top strand (and by symmetry, on the bottom strand).
$$
\text{Before cut: }
\begin{array}{ccc}
5' & - & \text{G G A T C C} & - & 3' \\
3' & - & \text{C C T A G G} & - & 5'
\end{array}
$$
The cleavage pattern `5'-G/GATCC-3'` means the cut occurs after the first G. This results in:
$$
\begin{array}{ccc}
5' & - & \text{G} \\
3' & - & \text{C C T A G}
\end{array}
\quad \text{and} \quad
\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{G A T C C} & - & 3' \\
\text{G} & - & 5'
\end{array}
$$
This produces a 4-nucleotide sticky end with the sequence 5'-GATC-3'. The GOI fragment will have this type of end on both sides.

Step 2: Analyze the cleavage by BglII.
The BglII recognition sequence is 5'-AGATCT-3'. Its complementary strand is 3'-TCTAGA-5'. The enzyme cleaves after the first A.
$$
\text{Before cut: }
\begin{array}{ccc}
5' & - & \text{A G A T C T} & - & 3' \\
3' & - & \text{T C T A G A} & - & 5'
\end{array}
$$
The cleavage pattern `5'-A/GATCT-3'` means the cut occurs after the A. This results in:
$$
\begin{array}{ccc}
5' & - & \text{A} \\
3' & - & \text{T C T A G}
\end{array}
\quad \text{and} \quad
\begin{array}{ccc}
\text{G A T C T} & - & 3' \\
\text{A} & - & 5'
\end{array}
$$
This also produces a 4-nucleotide sticky end with the sequence 5'-GATC-3'. The linearized vector will have this type of end.

Step 3: Analyze the ligation of the two different ends.
The sticky ends from both BamHI and BglII are 5'-GATC-3'. Because these single-stranded overhangs are identical, they are "compatible" and can anneal (pair up) through hydrogen bonds. DNA ligase can then seal the nicks in the sugar-phosphate backbone.

Let's construct the sequence at the junction. We take the end of the vector (from BglII digest) and ligate it to the end of the GOI insert (from BamHI digest).

Vector end:
$$
\begin{array}{l}
5' \text{...vector... A} \\
3' \text{...vector... T C T A G}
\end{array}
$$

Insert end:
$$
\begin{array}{r}
\text{G A T C C ...insert...} 3' \\
\text{G ...insert...} 5'
\end{array}
$$

When these anneal and are ligated, the new sequence is formed:
$$
\begin{array}{l}
5' \text{...vector... A} \\
3' \text{...vector... T C T A G}
\end{array}
\begin{array}{r}
\text{G A T C C ...insert...} 3' \\
\text{G ...insert...} 5'
\end{array}
\implies
\begin{array}{ccc}
5' & - & \text{vector... A G A T C C ...insert} & - & 3' \\
3' & - & \text{vector... T C T A G G ...insert} & - & 5'
\end{array}
$$
The new double-stranded DNA sequence at the junction is 5'-AGATCC-3' on one strand and 3'-TCTAGG-5' on the other.

Step 4: Evaluate the options based on the new junction sequence.
The new sequence is 5'-AGATCC-3'.
- **BamHI recognition site:** 5'-GGATCC-3'. The new sequence differs at the first base (A vs. G). Thus, it cannot be cut by BamHI.
- **BglII recognition site:** 5'-AGATCT-3'. The new sequence differs at the last base (C vs. T). Thus, it cannot be cut by BglII.

Now we can evaluate the statements:
A. False. The junction cannot be cleaved by BamHI.
B. False. The junction cannot be cleaved by BglII.
C. False. Since neither enzyme can cut the new junction, the ligation is not reversible using these specific enzymes.
D. True. The new sequence is a hybrid of the original two sites and, as shown above, is resistant to cleavage by both BamHI and BglII.

E. True. We must check if the new junction contains the recognition site for Sau3AI, which is 5'-/GATC-3'. The core recognition sequence is `GATC`. Let's look at our new junction sequence: 5'-A**GATC**C-3'. It clearly contains the `GATC` sequence. Therefore, the enzyme Sau3AI would be able to recognize and cleave this site.

Since the question asks for all correct statements, both D and E are correct.
